The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Watch shop attacked
                                                                                                            Watch shop attacked
          A STAFF REPORTER                          The damaged signboard of the Taratala watch showroom, the target of mob fury on Wednesday. A Telegraph picture                                  
	A 350-strong mob damaged the signboard and flower pots of a watch showroom in Taratala on Wednesday afternoon, alleging that the company had cheated them.        
	The protesters, all local residents, said the showroom had sold them coupons priced Rs 5 on New Years eve, with the promise that those who would win a lottery would be given attractive prizes.        
	But the winners, who thronged the showroom on Wednesday for the gifts, were enraged when the authorities handed them chocolates and diaries.        
	The watch company had sold hundreds of coupons, promising attractive gifts to those who would win a lottery, said Asim Sarkar, a local resident. The winners were shocked on opening the gift boxes  the items inside were far below their expectation. The company has cheated them.        
	An officer of Behala police station said around 350 protesters damaged the signboard of the showroom and the flower pots in front of it.        
	Raising slogans against the company, they tried to enter the shop but were stopped by the police. The residents demanded that the gift boxes be replaced. The protest was finally withdrawn around 5.30pm, following persuasion by the police, the officer added.        
	Praveen Kumar, the superintendent of South 24-Parganas police, said: The shop suffered minor damage. No one has been arrested. A probe has been ordered.                                                                                                                                                                           
